---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-colombia', text: 'Leaving Colombian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'currency-matters', text: 'Currency Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Latin America Insurance', href: '/best/latin-america-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Spanish Expat Insurance', href: '/best/spanish-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'spanishSupport', header: 'Spanish Support' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'colombiaCoverage', header: 'Colombia Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', spanishSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Strong', colombiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$175/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', spanishSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Excellent', colombiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$195/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', spanishSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Good', colombiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$170/mo' },
  { provider: 'April International', spanishSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Good', colombiaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$160/mo' },
  { provider: 'Seguros Bolivar', spanishSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Limited', colombiaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$120/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Colombian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Colombian expats. Find coverage for the US, Spain, and other destinations with Spanish language support."
  headline="Best Insurance for Colombian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Colombian communities abroad are growing rapidly. Here's how to stay protected in the US, Spain, and beyond while keeping your options open."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/colombian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Colombian expats are found in significant numbers in the US, Spain, Chile, and other countries. USD-denominated coverage provides stability against peso volatility. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Colombian expats. Full Spanish support, strong US networks, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent networks worldwide. Spanish support available.</li>
    <li><strong>April International:</strong> French insurer with excellent Spanish support. Good for Spain and Latin America.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong European networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Seguros Bolivar:</strong> Colombian insurer with some international options. Familiar brand, includes Colombia.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="US Healthcare Reality"
    description="The US has a large Colombian community, especially in Florida, New York, and New Jersey. US healthcare is extremely expensive—a hospital stay can cost $50,000-$200,000+. Comprehensive coverage is essential."
    buttonText="Get US Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-colombia">Leaving Colombian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Colombia has a mandatory health insurance system. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>EPS (Entidades Promotoras de Salud)</h3>
  <p>
    Colombia's mandatory health insurance through EPS provides coverage for employed and contributing members. EPS coverage only works in Colombia—there's no international coverage. Moving abroad ends practical access.
  </p>

  <h3>Contributory vs Subsidized</h3>
  <p>
    If you're in the contributory regime (paying through employment), your contributions stop when you leave Colombia. You lose EPS coverage. The subsidized regime only applies to Colombia residents.
  </p>

  <h3>Prepaid Medicine (Medicina Prepagada)</h3>
  <p>
    If you have Colombian prepaid medicine (Colsanitas, Coomeva Prepagada, Colmedica), check international coverage terms. Most provide limited international emergency coverage—typically 30-90 days. Long-term stays abroad need dedicated international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Maintaining Colombian Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    You can sometimes maintain EPS or prepaid coverage while abroad for short periods. This is useful for visits home but doesn't solve international coverage needs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="currency-matters">Currency Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Currency stability matters for Colombian expats:
  </p>

  <h3>Peso Volatility</h3>
  <p>
    The Colombian peso has experienced significant fluctuations. Peso-denominated coverage can change value unpredictably. USD-denominated international insurance provides stability.
  </p>

  <h3>USD-Denominated Benefits</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage limits maintain their purchasing power</li>
    <li>Premiums are predictable in hard currency</li>
    <li>Claims paid at actual international costs</li>
    <li>Protection against currency movements</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Payment Options</h3>
  <p>
    International insurers accept various payment methods:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>International credit cards</li>
    <li>Wire transfers</li>
    <li>Payment from US or destination country income</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Spanish Language Support</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Look for insurers with full Spanish-language support—Cigna and April International offer excellent Spanish service. This matters during medical emergencies when communication is critical.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive USD-denominated coverage with full Spanish-language support. Strong US networks (critical for Florida-based Colombians) and global coverage. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 Spanish service for support and claims. Colombia coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Colombian expats who want reliable global coverage with native Spanish support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent US networks. Spanish support is available. Service quality is outstanding with comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium positioning. Best for professionals who can afford the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Colombian professionals who want top-tier coverage, especially in the US.
  </p>

  <h3>April International</h3>
  <p>
    April International is a French insurer with excellent Spanish-language support. Strong presence in Spanish-speaking markets. Good EU networks and competitive pricing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Popular among Latin American expats in Europe and the Americas.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Colombian expats in Spain or Europe who want full Spanish support.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Spanish support available. Strong European networks make this suitable for Colombian expats in Spain.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Colombian expats seeking good value, especially in Europe.
  </p>

  <h3>Seguros Bolivar</h3>
  <p>
    Seguros Bolivar is a major Colombian insurer offering some international products. Full Spanish service, familiar brand, Colombia coverage included. International networks are more limited than global insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Colombian expats who prefer familiar Colombian service and primarily need Colombia coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get USD-denominated quotes from multiple providers to find the best balance of coverage, Spanish support, and price."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Colombian expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Largest Colombian diaspora, especially in Florida (Miami, Fort Lauderdale), New York, and New Jersey. US healthcare is extremely expensive—comprehensive coverage is essential. Many Colombian doctors practice in these areas.
  </p>

  <h3>Spain</h3>
  <p>
    Historical and linguistic ties make Spain popular. Spanish healthcare covers legal residents. Many Colombians supplement with private insurance for faster access. Madrid and Barcelona have Colombian communities.
  </p>

  <h3>Chile</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Colombian community. Chilean healthcare requires private insurance (ISAPRE) or public coverage (FONASA). International insurance covers the initial period.
  </p>

  <h3>Ecuador</h3>
  <p>
    Close proximity and cultural similarities. Ecuadorian healthcare is accessible but limited. International insurance provides better coverage than local options.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does my EPS cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. EPS only covers care in Colombia. You need dedicated international health insurance for coverage while living abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my prepaid medicine abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Colombian prepaid plans provide limited international coverage (typically emergency only for 30-90 days). Long-term stays need proper international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I get USD or peso coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">USD is recommended. Peso volatility can erode coverage value. USD policies maintain purchasing power regardless of exchange rate movements.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Colombia visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer Colombia as a coverage region. Seguros Bolivar includes it automatically. Confirm details with your chosen provider.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Spanish support important?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In medical emergencies, native language support reduces stress and misunderstandings. Cigna and April offer full Spanish service.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Colombian doctors in the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, especially in Miami, New York, and other cities with large Colombian communities. Your insurer covers any qualified doctor.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Colombian expats need comprehensive USD-denominated international insurance—Colombian coverage doesn't work abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for full Spanish support and strong US networks.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford the best. <strong>April International</strong> is excellent for Spain-bound expats. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value for European destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose USD-denominated coverage to protect against peso volatility. Prioritize Spanish-language support for easier communication during medical situations.
  </p>

</PageShell>
